Ford_Bike_Data¶

Introduction¶

Ford GoBike is the Bay Area's new bike share system, with thousands of public bikes for use across San Francisco, East Bay and San Jose. Renting Bikes is designed with convenience in mind. it’s a fun and affordable way to get around town.It aslo offers Single Ride is 2 dollars per day which is great for one way trip, Monthly Memberships is 15 dollars per month for its good deal for locals and Access Pass for 10 dollars which is perfect for exploring.

About Dataset¶

I chose Ford GoBike System Data as my source data This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system.Multiple data files will need to be joined together if a full year’s coverage is desired. The features included in the dataset : Trip Duration (seconds) , Start Time and Date , End Time and Date , Start Station ID , Start Station Name , Start Station Latitude , Start Station Longitude , End Station ID , End Station Name, End Station Latitude , End Station Longitude , Bike ID , User Type (Subscriber or Customer) and bike_share_for_all_trip(Yes or No).

Sharing bike during the Trip¶

In [228]:
bike_share = bike_data_clean.bike_share_for_all_trip.value_counts()

plt.figure(figsize = (8,6), dpi =90)
# we are plotting the figure by specifying the figure size and resolution

plt.title('% of bike sharing',fontsize=18);
# title for the graph

colors = ['r','b']
# setting the color for each portion of the piechart

plt.pie(bike_share.values,labels=bike_share.index,colors = colors,autopct = '%1.1f%%');
# plotting piechart  with respective color for their portion

We see that 91.3% of the users did not share the bike during trip while 8.7% of the users have shared the bike.¶

plt.xlabel('Month', fontsize = 12)

# we are specifying the name for the title of the graph

# we are plotting the line graph

plt.xticks(np.arange(1,13));
# setting the tick labels for the x-axis

We see that most number of rides were taken in the month of October while least number of rides were taken in the month of January¶

Monthly Bike rides vs User_types¶

In [233]:
monthly_user_types = bike_data_clean.groupby(['start_time_month' , 'user_type']).size().reset_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(10,7),dpi = 75)

colors = {'Subscriber' : 'Red' , 'Customer' : 'Blue'}

ax = sns.pointplot(x='start_time_month',y = 0, hue = 'user_type' , palette = colors , data = monthly_user_types)

plt.title('Bike Rides by Users in each month' , fontsize = 18)

plt.xlabel('Month' , fontsize = 12)

plt.ylabel('Frequency of bike rides' , fontsize = 12)

ax.legend().set_title('User Type')

1) We see that most number of rides taken by Customers were in the month of July while least number of rides were taken in the month of January.¶

2) We see that most number of rides taken by Subscribers were in the month of October while least number of rides were taken in the month of January.¶

Day vs Month Vs Subscriber¶

In [238]:
subscriber = bike_data_clean.query('user_type == "Subscriber"').groupby(['start_time_month','start_time_day']).agg({'bike_id'
             : 'count'}).rename(columns={'bike_id':'count'}).reset_index()

subscriber_pivot = subscriber.pivot_table(index = 'start_time_day' , columns = 'start_time_month' , values = 'count')

plt.figure(figsize = (10,10) ,dpi =100 )

sns.heatmap(subscriber_pivot,  annot=True, fmt='.0f',linewidths = .5 , annot_kws={"size": 14} );

plt.title('Day vs Month Vs Subscriber')

plt.xlabel('Month', labelpad=16)

plt.ylabel('Day', labelpad=16)

plt.yticks(rotation=0)

Conclusion¶

We see that most of the users are subscribes who contribute 85 % of the total dataset while customers contribute 15%¶

We see that most of the users have not shared their bike rides which contribute 91 % and the users who have shared the bike ride contribute 9%¶

We see that most of the subscribers made bike rides on 26th of June 2018 i.e. 7173 bike rides¶

We see that most of the subscribers made bike rides on 10th of May 2018 i.e. 1732 bike rides.¶¶
